    "body": "@joshaber @kevinsawicki \r\n\r\n> Is there a roughly similar equivalent UI/flow on Windows?\r\n\r\nThe first flow that came to mind was from Fiddler - a HTTP debugging app for Windows. To decrypt HTTPS traffic it needs to install a trusted root certificate so that it can act as a proxy and rewrite HTTPS requests on-the-fly.\r\n\r\nHere's the flow it uses:\r\n\r\n- First, a couple of clear warning messages:\r\n\r\n![](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/359239/24635905/f443ecba-1919-11e7-9e3b-64bd41026a4a.png)\r\n![](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/359239/24635908/f56f4a1c-1919-11e7-81d0-18afa227a2c5.png)\r\n\r\n - Then an external program launches elevated to install the certificate (because trusted root):\r\n\r\n![](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/359239/24635909/f57e120e-1919-11e7-9ec8-2b8cc40198d1.png)\r\n\r\n - This then confirms again that you want to do what you wanted:\r\n \r\n![](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/359239/24635906/f4e0be82-1919-11e7-95a4-d76aec2bc761.png)\r\n\r\n - And you're done:\r\n\r\n![](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/359239/24635907/f55be1ac-1919-11e7-9259-9a350632e905.png)\r\n\r\nUnfortunately I haven't found a good equivalent on Windows to the unified \"here's the details, do you trust this cert?\" screenshot from @joshaber above:\r\n\r\n![](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/13760/24570136/eb8d795e-1637-11e7-9953-08e916b1fde2.png)\r\n\r\nBut I'll report back soon on what I can find..."
